Here's a clean approach using merged `ResourceDictionary` swapping:

**1. Define each theme as a separate ResourceDictionary:**

```xml
<!-- Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
                    x:Class="MyApp.Themes.LightTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Themes/DarkTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...  x:Class="MyApp.Themes.DarkTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#1E1E1E</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#E0E0E0</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#4CC2FF</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Themes/HighContrastTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...  x:Class="MyApp.Themes.HighContrastTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#000000</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#FFFF00</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

**2. Create a theme service to swap dictionaries at runtime:**

```csharp
// Services/ThemeService.cs
using MyApp.Themes;

namespace MyApp.Services;

public enum AppTheme { Light, Dark, HighContrast }

public static class ThemeService
{
    private static ResourceDictionary? _currentTheme;

    public static void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        if (_currentTheme is not null)
            mergedDicts.Remove(_currentTheme);

        _currentTheme = theme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Dark         => new DarkTheme(),
            AppTheme.HighContrast => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _                     => new LightTheme(),
        };

        mergedDicts.Add(_currentTheme);

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("app_theme", theme.ToString());
    }

    public static void LoadSavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("app_theme", nameof(AppTheme.Light));
        if (Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(saved, out var theme))
            ApplyTheme(theme);
        else
            ApplyTheme(AppTheme.Light);
    }
}
```

**3. Apply the saved theme on startup in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        ThemeService.LoadSavedTheme();
    }
}
```

**4. Use `DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) in your XAML so changes propagate immediately:**

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label Text="Hello" TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryText}" />
    <Button BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource AccentColor}" Text="Go" />
</ContentPage>
```

**5. Wire up your settings page:**

```xml
<!-- SettingsPage.xaml -->
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" Title="Theme"
        SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged">
    <Picker.ItemsSource>
        <x:Array Type="{x:Type x:String}">
            <x:String>Light</x:String>
            <x:String>Dark</x:String>
            <x:String>HighContrast</x:String>
        </x:Array>
    </Picker.ItemsSource>
</Picker>
```

```csharp
// SettingsPage.xaml.cs
void OnThemeChanged(object? sender, EventArgs e)
{
    if (ThemePicker.SelectedIndex < 0) return;

    var theme = ThemePicker.SelectedIndex switch
    {
        1 => AppTheme.Dark,
        2 => AppTheme.HighContrast,
        _ => AppTheme.Light,
    };

    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(theme);
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`DynamicResource`** is essential — it re-evaluates when the dictionary changes. `StaticResource` won't update.
- Every theme dictionary must define the **same keys**; missing keys fall through to `App.xaml` defaults.
- `Preferences` persists the choice across launches.
- For `Style` objects that reference theme colors, define them in `App.xaml` using `DynamicResource` bindings so they also react to swaps.
